The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether the name of the country should be changed to the "Republic of Northern Macedonia", which would resolve a decades of old dispute with Greece which has prevented its attempt to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia, claiming that the name of its neighbour in the north constitutes a requirement on its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments concluded an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents claim that the change of name would undermine the identity of the slave majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said that he will not vote in the referendum, and a boycott campaign has led to doubts whether the minimum 50% participation required for the referendum to be considered valid will be achieved.
The question of the ballot in the referendum is: "Are you in favour of membership of NATO and the EU with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
However, the supporters of the change of names, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth changing the name if it makes it possible for Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia was divided, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they will follow the outcome so that it is considered decisive.
The change of names requires a majority of two thirds of Parliament.
According to the State Election Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1 p.m.
However, the participation was only 16 per cent, compared with 34 per cent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66 per cent of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital of Skopje.
The Prime Minister of Macedonia Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko will vote in the referendum in Macedonia on the change of name, which would open the way for NATO and the European Union membership in Strumica, Macedonia, 30 September 2018.
Outside the Skopje Parliament, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, organized a small scene and placed chairs in front of the tents set up by the boycotts of the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to join the head in the air, not sneak through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership in NATO would lead to the necessary investment in Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I believe that the absolute majority will vote in favour, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," said Zaev when he voted.
He said a "Yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future."
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Survey, between 30 and 43 per cent of voters thought to vote in the referendum, which falls under the minimum participation required.
According to another survey carried out by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57 per cent of the participants were planning to vote on Sunday.
70 percent of them were going to vote in favour.
